The author of this blog post is a little confused about embedded structs. His examples of <i>has-a</i> and <i>is-a</i> are both <i>has-a</i>&#x27;s, and the syntax change involved (leaving off a name for the embedded type) doesn&#x27;t actually do anything.<p><pre><code>  type Person struct {
     Name string
     Address Address
  }
</code></pre>
is equivalent to<p><pre><code>  type Person struct {
     Name string
     Address
  }
</code></pre>
And in fact, these are equivalent too:<p><pre><code>  p.Address.Zip = &quot;01313&quot;

  p.Zip = &quot;01313&quot;
</code></pre>
<a href="http://play.golang.org/p/aKH3YxT5Mb" rel="nofollow">http://play.golang.org/p/aKH3YxT5Mb</a><p>Go doesn&#x27;t really support <i>is-a</i> for structs, as pointed out elsewhere in the comments here. Interface implementation is the only way to get the sort of &quot;this type can be substituted for this other type&quot; idea that <i>is-a</i> inheritance provides in other languages.
